It depends on the interface. It's really hard to do everything in one app. There is not a lot of space in mobile. It either gets too confusing or so hidden that no one uses it
I'll continue to write my random musings here....
I wish we could have something like that again.
The data rate of the satellite Usenet feed was 45Mbit/s at the time.

I remember when I was 18, I used to receive Usenet by satellite, it was transmitted by a company called Cidera on the Sirius satellite at 5 degrees East. You could just use any DVB-S receiver card to pick it up, completely unencrypted, it used multicast UDP as a transport, with a Those days were amazing, you could read anything you wanted, completely anonymously, without any possibility of government surveillance. The freedom you had was just incredible, to be able to watch all the messages, what people were sending worldwide. To explore anything you wanted, completely unfettered.
This Nostr thing feels like the early days of the Internet again.... If we could only have a satellite DVB-S2 feed of it...
I have my own crazy domain specific language, which emits Verilog, to be synthesized using Yosys, where NextPNR will generate the bitstream for the FPGA....
Anyway, back to playing around with FPGAs now....

And the VDSL2 modem should be able to transmit on any HF frequency, with a maximum power of 20dBm. Which still might be good enough if there's a receiver station nearby. I only want the BPSK uplink data rate to be 300bps or so, which is more than enough to send text. And you can compress it, with a pre-filled dictionary-based compression algorithm, to further reduce the size of it.

So it can give us an 'off grid' darknet, that doesn't need Internet access in order to send messages. And to receive is totally anonymous. So you can read whatever you want without ever the government NSA / GHCQ, etc. being able to tell. No need to worry if the security of the darknet has been broken. If you have an air gapped receiver it's nearly impossible to find out.

And for the downlink, it can be by satellite. Where you can see all the messages, as described above. The only problem is that satellite bandwidth is very expensive, however at present the Nostr message volumes are quite low, they can be compressed too.
That is my idea, what I've been thinking of for a while....

Once this preamble has been found, we then listen on the bin, looking for BPSK modulated message data. This can be then forwarded to Nostr. And since it only uses a cheap VDSL2 modem and a PC as a receive, we can have hundreds, possibly thousands of receivers worldwide. Obviously it will be necessary to deduplicate the messages. But now we can have a worldwide receiver network, and to transmit all you need is a HF radio, and you can transmit on almost any frequency as an uplink, just whatever is unused. And you can use the 27MHz band, and possibly 13.56MHz as license free uplink frequencies. You can just pick any frequency, and it will be detected automatically.

So once we have the raw data delivered to a desktop PC, we can use a GPU to do a FFT of the entire radio spectrum from 0-30MHz. And we can look for a specific preamble sequence on each bin. So in effect we are monitoring the entire radio spectrum at once.

I have the source code to Lantiq VDSL2 modem firmware, yes the core that runs the modem. I wonder if we can turn the VDSL modem in to a SDR, by connecting an antenna to the telephone jack on the modem. There's a 16 bit ADC in there, I wonder if it's possible to get at the raw samples and stream them over UDP via Gigabit Ethernet. That means we have a low cost equivalent to the Web SDR http://websdr.ewi.utwente.nl:8901/
And to transmit, we could use LoRaWAN or HF radio maybe for that? So you can communicate without needing an Internet connection.
All you need is a DVB-S2 receiver or SDR and a satellite dish. And no internet connection required to receive it.
It would be nice if we had a service like https://blocksat.info/ to broadcast compressed Nostr messages over satellite worldwide. That way you can anonymously receive the data, with complete privacy.
On https://nostr.io/stats there appears to be another sudden in usage just recently.

I like how Nostr requires no account sign up, no email verification, no phone number. It just works like that, as long as you have an Internet connection, you can participate. No central authority to control anything. I think that's amazing.
Really interesting to be able to see what people are saying worldwide.... Around 3-4 messages per second at present, across all the above relays I listed.

Ciao a tutti,

Che ne pensate di questo logo per Nostr? 

E' stato creato dal designer Andrea Nicolini, (aka Bembureda, npub104fpzfgtc4h272p66uye2nhjes622x7dduk97g8re5h8gmmv2pnsqdq2a2, https://bembureda.dribbble.com).

Credo che avere un logo per Nostr possa facilitarne diffusione e adozione. 

Piccolo esempio: un logo rende la vita più semplice a chi voglia mettere un’icona Nostr nel proprio sito o nel proprio profilo a fianco di quelle di LinkedIn, Facebook, …

Anteprima: https://nostr.build/i/0013214867939154ec657baf71673eba08e6ab655993f5848553651f5c57543b.jpg

Bello, no? Puoi scaricarlo in diversi formati e colori da qui:

https://github.com/mbarulli/nostr-logo/

Il tutto rilasciato con licenza CC0, che consente qualunque tipo di utilizzo senza restrizioni.

Se ti piace, inizia ad utilizzarlo e spargi la voce! Grazie!
